04626nam a22006375i 9780231555197DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315551977 a10.7312/negr203702doi  a(DE-B1597)650102  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a338.4766322231 aHannan, Michael T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWine Markets :bGenres and Identities /cMichael T. Hannan, Giacomo Negro. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b40 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE Genres and Market Identities -- tCHAPTER TWO Barolo and Barbaresco -- tCHAPTER THREE The Barolo Wars -- tCHAPTER FOUR Mobilization of Collective Market Identities -- tCHAPTER FIVE Genre Spanning, Ambiguity, and Valuation -- tCHAPTER SIX Brunello di Montalcino -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Tradition, Modernity, and the Scandal -- tCHAPTER EIGHT Alsace -- tCHAPTER NINE Biodynamic and Organic Winemaking -- tCHAPTER TEN Why Biodynamics? Category Signals and Audience Response -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN Community Structure, Social Movements, and Market Identities -- tCHAPTER TWELVE Coda -- tAppendix: Data Sources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world of wine encompasses endless variety. Consumers want to understand what makes one bottle of wine different from another; vintners need to know how to communicate what makes their product distinctive. Drawing on a decade of fieldwork in Italy and France as well as interviews with critics and analysis of market data, Giacomo Negro, Michael T. Hannan, and Susan Olzak provide an unprecedented sociological account of the dynamics of wine markets. They demonstrate how the concepts of genre and collective identity illuminate producers’ choices, whether they are selling traditional or nonconventional wines.Winemakers face a fundamental choice: produce an existing style and develop an identity as a proponent of tradition or embrace foreign, new, or emerging categories and be seen as an innovator. To explain this dilemma, Negro, Hannan, and Olzak develop the notion of wine genres, or shared understandings among producers and the public. Genres emerge through the social structure of production, including factors such as group solidarity, social cohesion, and collective action, and become key reference points for critics and consumers. Wine Markets features case studies of the creation of a modern wine genre and a countermovement against modernism in Piedmont, the failure of producers of Brunello di Montalcino in Tuscany to define a clear collective identity, and the emergence of the biodynamic wine movement in Alsace. This book not only offers keen sociological insight into the wine world but also sheds new light on the logic of markets and organizations more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aWine and wine makingxSocial aspects. 0aWine and wine making-Social aspects. 0aWine industryxSocial aspects. 0aWine industry-Social aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aNegro, Giacomo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOlzak, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/negr2037040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555197423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555197/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPD